Major Mukund Varadarajan was a decorated officer in the Indian Army who was posthumously awarded the Ashok Chakra, India's highest peacetime military decoration. He was known for his bravery and leadership, particularly during counter-insurgency operations in Jammu and Kashmir.

Key Points about Major Mukund Varadarajan:
Birth and Early Life: Mukund was born on April 12, 1983, in Chennai, Tamil Nadu. He completed his schooling in Chennai and later graduated with a degree in business administration before joining the Indian Army.

Army Career: He was commissioned into the 22nd Battalion of the Rajput Regiment, a highly reputed unit of the Indian Army. Mukund Varadarajan was known for his professionalism, dedication, and courage in various operations.

Operation in Jammu and Kashmir: On April 25, 2014, Major Mukund led a unit in a counter-insurgency operation in the Shopian district of Jammu and Kashmir. His team successfully eliminated three terrorists hiding in a house but came under heavy fire during the operation. In the fierce gunfight, he sustained severe injuries but continued to lead the operation, displaying exceptional bravery. He eventually succumbed to his injuries.